title: ggdemetra: extending ggplot2 to perform seasonal adjustment with RJDemetra
text: functions common parameters especially defined seasonal adjustment method: method method used seasonal adjustment: X-13ARIMA (method = "x13", default) TRAMO-SEATS (method = "tramoseats"). spec seasonal adjustment specification. can name pre-defined specification (see ?RJDemetra::x13 ?RJDemetra::tramoseats) user-defined specification created RJDemetra (RJDemetra::x13_spec RJDemetra::tramoseats_spec). frequency frequency input time series. default, frequency computed message printed one chosen (use message = FALSE suppress message). following examples, data used French industrial production index. default, seasonal adjustment processed X-13ARIMA pre-defined specification "RSA5c (automatic log detection, automatic ARIMA outliers detection trading day easter adjustment). However, industrial production working day effect economic sense trading day effect gradual effect easter make economic sense aggregated series. specification used X-13ARIMA spec = RJDemetra::x13_spec("RSA3", tradingdays.option = "WorkingDays"). new data seasonal adjustment specification specified (method specification), parameters inherited previous defined: therefore need specify parameter .
code: library(ggplot2) library(ggdemetra) p_ipi_fr <- ggplot(data = ipi_c_eu_df, mapping = aes(x = date, y = FR)) +     geom_line() +     labs(title = "Seasonal adjustment of the French industrial production index",          x = NULL, y = NULL) p_ipi_fr

what: Add the result of the seasonal adjusment
title: ggdemetra: extending ggplot2 to perform seasonal adjustment with RJDemetra
text: default geom_sa() adds seasonal adjusted time series:  add components seasonal adjustment, use component parameter geom_sa() (see ?RJDemetra::user_defined_variables() availables parameters). example, add forecasts input data seasonal adjusted series:
code: spec <- RJDemetra::x13_spec("RSA3", tradingdays.option = "WorkingDays") p_ipi_fr +     geom_sa(color = "#155692",             spec = spec) #> Frequency used: 12 p_sa <- p_ipi_fr +     geom_sa(component = "y_f", linetype = 2, message = FALSE,             spec = spec) +      geom_sa(component = "sa", color = "#155692") +     geom_sa(component = "sa_f", color = "#155692", linetype = 2) p_sa

what: Add the outliers to the plot
title: ggdemetra: extending ggplot2 to perform seasonal adjustment with RJDemetra
text: four differents geometrics add plot names outliers used pre-adjustment process: geom = "text" (default) adds directly names outliers geom = "label" draws rectangle behind names, making easier read. geom = "text_repel" geom = "label_repel" text labels repel away away data points (see ?ggrepel::geom_label_repel). example, 3 outliers:  can plotted readable way using parameters ggrepel::geom_label_repel:  Use parameters first_date last_date outliers precise time interval. example, plot outliers 2009 use first_date = 2009:
code: p_sa + geom_outlier(geom = "label") p_sa +      geom_outlier(geom = "label_repel",                  ylim = c(NA, 65),                   arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.03, "npc"),                                type = "closed", ends = "last")) p_sa +      geom_outlier(geom = "label_repel",                  first_date = 2009,                  ylim = c(NA, 65),                   arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.03, "npc"),                                type = "closed", ends = "last"))

what: Add a table with some diagnostics
title: ggdemetra: extending ggplot2 to perform seasonal adjustment with RJDemetra
text: table diagnostics seasonal adjustment process can added geom_diagnostics(). desired diagnostics added diagnostics parameter (see ?RJDemetra::user_defined_variables() availables diagnostics). example, add result X-11 combined test p-values residual seasonality qs f tests:  customize names diagnostics plot, pass named vector diagnostics parameter:  add table plot, can example use gridExtra::grid.arrange():
code: diagnostics <- c("diagnostics.combined.all.summary", "diagnostics.qs", "diagnostics.ftest") p_sa +      geom_diagnostics(diagnostics = diagnostics,                      ymin = 58, ymax = 72, xmin = 2010,                      table_theme = gridExtra::ttheme_default(base_size = 8)) diagnostics <- c(`Combined test` = "diagnostics.combined.all.summary",                  `Residual qs-test (p-value)` = "diagnostics.qs",                  `Residual f-test (p-value)` = "diagnostics.ftest") p_sa +      geom_diagnostics(diagnostics = diagnostics,                      ymin = 58, ymax = 72, xmin = 2010,                      table_theme = gridExtra::ttheme_default(base_size = 8)) p_diag <- ggplot(data = ipi_c_eu_df, mapping = aes(x = date, y = FR))  +     geom_diagnostics(diagnostics = diagnostics,                      spec = spec, frequency = 12,                      table_theme = gridExtra::ttheme_default(base_size = 8)) +      theme_void()      gridExtra::grid.arrange(p_sa, p_diag,              nrow = 2, heights  = c(4, 1.5))

title: ggdemetra: extending ggplot2 to perform seasonal adjustment with RJDemetra
text: ggdemetra offers several function can used manipulate existing models. previous plots can initialized init_ggplot() function:  different components seasonal adjustment models can extracted calendar(), calendaradj(), irregular(), trendcycle(), seasonal(), seasonaladj(), trendcycle() raw().  SI-ratio plots can plotted siratioplot ggsiratioplot:  also autoplot() function:
code: mod <- RJDemetra::x13(ipi_c_eu[,"UK"], spec) init_ggplot(mod) +      geom_line(color =  "#F0B400") +     geom_sa(color =  "#155692") +     geom_arima(geom = "label",                x_arima = -Inf, y_arima = -Inf,                 vjust = -1, hjust = -0.1) data <- ts.union(raw(mod), raw(mod, forecast = TRUE),                  trendcycle(mod), trendcycle(mod, forecast = TRUE),                  seasonaladj(mod), seasonaladj(mod, forecast = TRUE)) colnames(data) <- c("y", "y_f",                     "t", "t_f",                     "sa", "sa_f") ggplot(data = ts2df(data), mapping = aes(x = date)) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = y), color =  "#F0B400", na.rm = TRUE) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = y_f), color =  "#F0B400", na.rm = TRUE, linetype = 2) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = t), color =  "#1E6C0B", na.rm = TRUE) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = t_f), color =  "#1E6C0B", na.rm = TRUE, linetype = 2) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = sa), color =  "#155692", na.rm = TRUE) +     geom_line(mapping = aes(y = sa_f), color =  "#155692", na.rm = TRUE, linetype = 2) +     theme_bw() ggsiratioplot(mod) autoplot(mod)

title: ggplot2 Extension for Seasonal and Trading Day Adjustment with RJDemetra
text: ggdemetra extension ggplot2 add seasonal adjustment statistics plots. seasonal adjustment process done RJDemetra R interface JDemetra+, seasonal adjustment software officially recommended members European Statistical System (ESS) European System Central Banks. RJDemetra implements two leading seasonal adjustment methods TRAMO/SEATS+ X-12ARIMA/X-13ARIMA-SEATS. 4 main functionnalities ggdemetra depending want add graphic: geom_sa(): add time series compute seasonal adjustment (trend, seasonal adjusted time series, etc.). geom_outlier(): add outliers used pre-adjustment process seasonal adjustment. geom_arima(): add ARIMA model used pre-adjustment process seasonal adjustment. geom_diagnostics(): add table containing diagnostics seasonal adjustment process.

title: ggplot2 Extension for Seasonal and Trading Day Adjustment with RJDemetra

code: # Install release version from CRAN install.packages("ggdemetra")  # Install development version from GitHub # install.packages("devtools") devtools::install_github("AQLT/ggdemetra")

title: ggplot2 Extension for Seasonal and Trading Day Adjustment with RJDemetra
text: default, seasonal adjustment made X-13-ARIMA pre-defined specification “RSA5c” (automatic log detection, automatic ARIMA outliers detection trading day easter adjustment). new data seasonal adjustment specification specified (method specification), parameters inherited previous defined: therefore need specify specification . following examples, seasonal adjustment perform X-13-ARIMA working day adjustment gradual easter effect adjustment (specification economic sense industrial production index). add seasonal adjusted series forecasts input data seasonal adjusted series:  add outliers bottom plot arrow data point estimated coefficients:  add ARIMA model:  add table diagnostics plot:  See vignette details. Note ts objects directly used ggplot2. convert ts mts object data.frame, can use ts2df() function. example, data ipi_c_eu_df used package obtained applying ts2df()function ipi_c_eu data available RJDemetra:
code: library(ggplot2) library(ggdemetra) spec <- RJDemetra::x13_spec("RSA3", tradingdays.option = "WorkingDays") p_ipi_fr <- ggplot(data = ipi_c_eu_df, mapping = aes(x = date, y = FR)) +     geom_line(color =  "#F0B400") +     labs(title = "Seasonal adjustment of the French industrial production index",          x = NULL, y = NULL) p_sa <- p_ipi_fr +     geom_sa(component = "y_f", linetype = 2,             spec = spec, frequency = 12, color =  "#F0B400") +      geom_sa(component = "sa", color = "#155692") +     geom_sa(component = "sa_f", color = "#155692", linetype = 2) p_sa p_sa +      geom_outlier(geom = "label_repel",                  coefficients = TRUE,                  ylim = c(NA, 65),                   arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.03, "npc"),                                type = "closed", ends = "last"),                  digits = 2) p_sa +      geom_arima(geom = "label",                x_arima = -Inf, y_arima = -Inf,                 vjust = -1, hjust = -0.1) diagnostics <- c(`Combined test` = "diagnostics.combined.all.summary",                  `Residual qs-test (p-value)` = "diagnostics.qs",                  `Residual f-test (p-value)` = "diagnostics.ftest") p_diag <- ggplot(data = ipi_c_eu_df, mapping = aes(x = date, y = FR)) +     geom_diagnostics(diagnostics = diagnostics,                      table_theme = gridExtra::ttheme_default(base_size = 8),                      spec = spec, frequency = 12) +      theme_void()      gridExtra::grid.arrange(p_sa, p_diag,              nrow = 2, heights  = c(4, 1.5)) ipi_c_eu_df <- ts2df(ipi_c_eu)
